hands_on_practices.solution:
1. The Hölder exponent at a point with a fixed sequence of choices $i_j\in\{1,2\}$ is
$$
\alpha
=\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{\ln\mu(I_n)}{\ln|I_n|}
=\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{\sum_{j=1}^n\ln p_{i_j}}{n\ln l}
=\frac{\overline{\ln p}}{\ln l}\,,
$$
where $\overline{\ln p}$ is the average of $\ln p_{i_j}$.  
2. Since $\ln p_1<\ln p_2$ and $\ln l<0$, the maximum Hölder exponent arises when all $i_j=1$, giving
$$
\alpha_{\max}
=\frac{\ln p_1}{\ln l}\,.
$$
3. Substituting $p_1=\tfrac14$ and $l=\tfrac13$,
$$
\alpha_{\max}
=\frac{\ln\!\bigl(\tfrac14\bigr)}{\ln\!\bigl(\tfrac13\bigr)}
=\frac{-2\ln2}{-\,\ln3}
=\frac{2\ln2}{\ln3}\,.
$$
